{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6aed47ad-56de-411b-a4b4-5f9643e6e8fa","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n**1. Exec into the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace` inside the container:**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**3. Find your process ID:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**4. Collect the trace:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**5. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**6. Analyze** by opening the `.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to Speedscope format:\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool install` fails (no SDK in the container), download the standalone `dotnet-trace` from the [.NET diagnostics releases](https://github.com/dotnet/diagnostics) or use a sidecar container with the SDK. You can also set `DOTNET_DiagnosticPorts` to enable cross-container collection.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fe31159d-6705-414d-886c-7939382d0d49","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":403,"requestId":"6413:13072B:25BDFF2:2AB9E73:69EC1416"},"id":"e856bc80-46e6-4258-82a8-aa5adbe72766","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:08:47.824Z","parentId":"00b2e188-299d-44e8-b5af-e2f6253804c8"}
